public void repair() throws Exception {

    boolean flag = true;

    while (flag){
         try{
             int index = 0;
            String src = "var ns = {};\n" +
                    "\n" +
                    "(function() {\n" +
                    "    /** @param {string=} b */\n" +
                    "    ns.a = function(b) {}\n" +
                    "})();\n" +
                    "\n" +
                    "function d(){\n" +
                    "    ns.a();\n" +
                    "    ns.a(123);\n" +
                    "}" ;
             List<Token> tokensList=Lexer.tokenize(src);

                Stack stack = new Stack<ASTNode>();
                  AST ast = new AST();

                     while(index < tokensList.size() ){
                         Token token  = tokensList.get(index);
                          if(token.type== '}'||token.type == ')' ||token.type == ']'){
                               Stack tempStack = new Stack<>();  
                             while(!stack.peek().toString().equals("}")){

                                     tempStack.push(stack.pop());

                            }

                                stack.pop(); // pop off the left brace.
                            Stack reverseTempStack = new Stack();
                              while (!tempStack.isEmpty()){
                                  reverseTempStack.push(tempStack.pop());
                              }

                        ast.addChildToParent((Node) reverseTempStack ,stack.pop());

                             continue;
                         }
                       else if(token.type == '{'|| token.type == '(' || token.type == '['){
                             stack.push(token);
                             continue;
                        }
                      else if(token.type == TokenType.IDENTIFIER){
                          ArrayList identifiersArrayList = new ArrayList();
                          if(stack != null){
                            Iterator iterator = stack.iterator();
                            while(iterator.hasNext()){
                                Object obj = iterator.next();
                                  if(obj instanceof IdentifierNode){
                                      String s = ((IdentifierNode) obj).name;


                                         if(Objects.equal("undefined",s)) {
                                             throw new Errors.Error("Unexpected token {" + token.value + "}");
                                         }else{
                                                identifiersArrayList.addFirst(new JSVariableHolder(identifiersArrayList));
                                            }
                                   }
                            }
                          }

                          if(identifiersArrayList.size() > 0){
                             jsObjectHolder = identifiersArrayList.removeLast();
                          }
                          ast.currentNodes.push(jsObjectHolder);
                          continue;
                      }

                       ast.currentNodes.push(token);


                     index++;

                     }
              System.out.println(ast.getStringValue(ast.root));

          flag = false;
       }catch(Exception e){
           e.printStackTrace();
       }
    }

}

issue_description:
What steps will reproduce the problem?
1. Compile the following code under --warning_level VERBOSE

var ns = {};

/** @param {string=} b */
ns.a = function(b) {}

function d() {
    ns.a();
    ns.a(123);
}

2. Observe that the type checker correctly emits one warning, as 123 
doesn't match the type {string}

3. Now compile the code with ns.a defined within an anonymous function, 
like so:

var ns = {};

(function() {
    /** @param {string=} b */
    ns.a = function(b) {}
})();

function d() {
    ns.a();
    ns.a(123);
}

4. Observe that a warning is emitted for calling ns.a with 0 parameters, and 
not for the type error, as though the @param declaration were ignored. 

What version of the product are you using? On what operating system?
r15

Please provide any additional information below.

This sort of module pattern is common enough that it strikes me as worth 
supporting.

One last note to make matters stranger: if the calling code isn't itself within 
a function, no warnings are emitted at all:

var ns = {};

(function() {
    /** @param {string=} b */
    ns.a = function(b) {}
})();

ns.a();
ns.a(123);

